    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the lower stems of your tomato plants are likely a sign of a nutrient deficiency, specifically iron or magnesium. These essential minerals can be leached out of the soil by excess water, especially if your plants are growing in a container. You can try adding a balanced fertilizer to the soil, but if the issue persists, it may be a sign of a more serious problem, such as root bound or overwatering. \n\nIt's also possible that the soil pH has become too acidic, which can cause nutrient deficiencies. You can check the pH level of your soil using a soil testing kit and adjust it accordingly. \n\nTo address the issue, I'd recommend repotting your tomatoes in a well-draining potting mix with a slightly acidic pH (around 6.0-6.8). This will help prevent further nutrient deficiencies and promote healthy root growth. \n\nOn the other hand, if your plants are thriving in their current conditions, it's possible that the yellowing leaves are simply a result of the natural aging process. In that case, you can try pruning the affected leaves to promote new growth and encourage the plant to focus its energy on producing fruit.",
