    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips. you mentioned the pH might be the issue though. if i use lime to bring the pH up, how much should i actually add to a standard 5 gallon bucket or a medium sized pot? i dont want to burn the roots or something.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When adjusting the pH of your soil, it's essential to do so gradually to avoid shocking the roots. A general rule of thumb is to add 1-2 pounds of lime per 100 square feet of soil surface area. For a 5-gallon bucket or a medium-sized pot, I'd recommend starting with a small amount, such as 1/4 to 1/2 cup of lime per bucket or pot. \n\nHowever, it's crucial to note that different types of lime have varying pH-raising capacities, so it's always best to use a soil test kit to determine the exact pH level of your soil. If your soil pH is significantly below 6.0, you may need to add more lime.\n\nTo avoid burning the roots, make sure to mix the lime thoroughly into the soil, and then water the soil well. You can also consider adding a small amount of dolomitic limestone, which releases calcium and magnesium slowly, providing a more balanced pH adjustment.\n\nRemember, it's always better to err on the side of caution when adjusting the pH of your soil. If you're unsure, you can also consider consulting with a local nursery or gardening expert for personalized advice.",
